        <div class="bylaws-intro">
          <p>Hamilton's STR regulations were added as Schedule 32 to the City's Business Licensing By-law (07-170) in January 2023. Here's what you need to know to operate legally.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bylaws-grid">
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>License Required</h3>
            <p>All STR operators must obtain a license from the City. Your license number must be displayed prominently in every listing and advertisement. Licenses are valid for one year and must be renewed annually.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>Principal Residence Only</h3>
            <p>You can only operate an STR at your principal residence, where you ordinarily reside, pay bills, and receive mail. Only one principal residence is permitted per operator, and corporations cannot hold operator licenses.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>$1 Million Insurance</h3>
            <p>Operators must maintain homeowners, condo, or renters insurance that includes STR coverage with minimum $1,000,000 liability per occurrence. The policy must include a clause notifying the City 30 days before cancellation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>Criminal Record Check</h3>
            <p>Your license application requires an original criminal record check (or certification that none exists). Convictions within the past 5 years may result in license denial.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>Guest Limits & Information</h3>
            <p>Maximum guest occupancy must be displayed in listings. You're required to provide guests with an information package including emergency contacts, house rules, and local bylaws.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>Fire Safety Requirements</h3>
            <p>A fire escape plan must be submitted with your application and posted on all floors. Working smoke alarms and CO detectors are required per Fire Code standards.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>Record Keeping</h3>
            <p>Operators must maintain records of all bookings for 3 years including: number of nights rented, nightly rates, and total prices charged. Records must be provided to the City within 30 days upon request.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bylaw-card">
            <h3>Mid-Term Alternative</h3>
            <p>Rentals of 28+ consecutive days are exempt from STR regulations. This is an excellent option for investment properties near McMaster University or Hamilton Health Sciences.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bylaws-cta">
